<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="484" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1727]" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1198,1223]" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">Etymology:</emphasis>
the Latin specific name is a masculine genitive form of the adjective 
<emphasis box="[1142,1226,1200,1223]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">crassus</emphasis>
, meaning thick or plump, referring to the thickening of some ventrites of the abdomen (
<emphasis box="[942,1018,1236,1259]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">ventris</emphasis>
, the genitive form of the Latin noun 
<emphasis box="[151,221,1272,1295]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">venter</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="484" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1727]" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1306,1331]" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The form of the male head with its short vertical frons, and long, obliquely sloping upper part is unlike any other member of the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[570,699,1342,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Platypodini">Platypodini</taxonomicName>
known to us, although a superficially similar head is found in the genus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Lea" authorityName="Lea" authorityYear="1910" box="[234,435,1378,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Notoplatypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[234,383,1378,1403]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">Notoplatypus</emphasis>
Lea
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Strohmeyer" authorityYear="1914" box="[453,609,1378,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Tesserocerini">Tesserocerini</taxonomicName>
). However, the elongate egg-shaped eye and vase-shaped elytra clearly relate the species to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schedl)" authorityName=": Schedl" authorityYear="1972" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" box="[384,690,1414,1439]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baiocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anaticeps">
<emphasis box="[384,583,1416,1439]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">Baiocis anaticeps</emphasis>
(Schedl)
</taxonomicName>
. The male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Beaver &amp; Liu" authorityYear="2018" box="[849,1024,1416,1439]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baiocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassiventris">
<emphasis box="[849,1024,1416,1439]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">B. crassiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the latter species by the absence of a transverse carina separating the frons from the vertex, the posterolateral process of the elytra is directed somewhat posteriorly rather than vertically, and the posterior margins of ventrites 2‒4 are raised and thickened to form transverse ridges, projecting as rounded lobes over the next posterior ventrite at the sides of the ridge. In 
<emphasis box="[293,438,1560,1583]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Schedl" authorityYear="1972" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" box="[293,434,1560,1583]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baiocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anaticeps">B. anaticeps</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the posterior margin of the second ventrite only is slightly thickened. The females of this species and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Schedl" authorityYear="1972" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" box="[293,434,1596,1619]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baiocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anaticeps">
<emphasis box="[293,434,1596,1619]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">B. anaticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Browne" authorityYear="1962" box="[948,1032,1596,1619]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baiocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[948,1032,1596,1619]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">Baiocis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the oval or egg-shaped eye. In female 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Beaver &amp; Liu" authorityYear="2018" box="[235,411,1632,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baiocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassiventris">
<emphasis box="[235,411,1632,1655]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">B. crassiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the head is longer than high, not deeper than long, and the elytra are 1.8 times as long as the pronotum, rather than 2.0‒2.1 times as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Schedl" authorityYear="1972" baseAuthorityName="Schedl" box="[660,798,1668,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Baiocis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anaticeps">
<emphasis box="[660,798,1668,1691]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="484">B. anaticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
